The mortality impact of the August 2003 heat wave in France: investigating the 
'harvesting' effect and other long-term consequences.

Toulemon L(1), Barbieri M.

Author information:
(1)Institut national d'études démographiques, 75980 Paris cedex, France. 
toulemon@ined.fr

In August 2003, Western Europe experienced a deadly heat wave. It is estimated 
that 15,000 people died in France from its direct effects. Applying an indirect 
estimation technique to the monthly number of deaths by sex, age, and place of 
residence for the period 1996-2003, we estimate the number of years that would 
have remained to those who died from the heat wave had they been spared. The 
paper also evaluates the role of the 'harvesting' effect of the 2003 heat wave 
in explaining the deficit of deaths recorded in 2004--estimated at 23,000 out of 
an expected total of 535,000 deaths. The harvesting effect was modest and 
accounted for fewer than 5,000 of the 'missing' deaths in 2004. The mortality 
decline in 2004 is thus due mainly to other factors. One hypothesis is that 
special efforts have been directed towards isolated older people as a 
consequence of the heat wave.

